Surds

1. Rational & irrational numbers

Special sets: identifying rational numbers

Is the following statement true or false: −130∈ℚ−130∈Q?

Answer: The statement is .
HINT: <no title>
[−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

The set of rational numbers includes any number which can be written as a fraction of two integers. This includes all integers, any decimal number which terminates, and any decimal number which has a repeating pattern.

STEP: <no title>
[−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

The set of rational numbers includes all numbers which can be written as a fraction of two integers, as long as the denominator is not zero. The definition looks like this: ℚ={ab:a,b∈ℤ,b≠0}Q={ab:a,b∈Z,b≠0}. Here is a summary of what this means:

  • the set of rational numbers includes:
    1. all fractions with integers in the numerator and denominator, as long as the denominator is not zero, for example: 12;−711;2005012;−711;20050
    2. all integers because integers can be written as fractions, for example 5=515=51
    3. all terminating decimal numbers, for example: 4,2;−1,5;3,509274654,2;−1,5;3,50927465
    4. all decimal numbers with a recurring pattern, for example: 0,3333…;2,6˙;6,5827827827…0,3333…;2,6˙;6,5827827827…
  • the set of rational numbers does not include:
    1. any fraction where the denominator is zero
    2. decimal numbers which go on forever without a repeating pattern, for example: 2,4681012…;3,14159265…2,4681012…;3,14159265…

In this question the number we must decide if −130−130 is an element of the rational numbers. −130−130 cannot be a rational number because of the zero in the denominator! In the definition of the rational numbers, the statement "b≠0b≠0" means that denominators of rational numbers may not be zero. In fact, dividing by zero always leads to an "undefined" answer.

The statement −130∈ℚ−130∈Q is False.

560560

Answer:
HINT: <no title>
[−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

If you can simplify the number, start by doing that. Then you must decide if the number can also be written as a fraction of two integers. If it can, then it is a rational number; if it cannot, then it is irrational.

STEP: <no title>
[−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

A fraction with a denominator equal to zero is neither rational nor irrational: it is "undefined," which means that it is not equal to anything.

Rational and irrational numbers

Is the following number rational, irrational or neither?

π7π7

Answer:
HINT: <no title>
[−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

If you can simplify the number, start by doing that. Then you must decide if the number can also be written as a fraction of two integers. If it can, then it is a rational number; if it cannot, then it is irrational.

STEP: <no title>
[−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

irrational numbers are the opposite of rational numbers: they cannot be written as a fraction with two integers. ππ itself is an irrational number: it is equal to 3,1415926…3,1415926…. If you work out the value of π7π7 with your calculator, you will find that it is quite a long decimal number. In fact, when you write an irrational number as a decimal, it will never terminate (end) and it will never repeat.

The correct answer is irrational.

Rational and irrational numbers

Is the following number rational, irrational or neither?

101101

Answer:
HINT: <no title>
[−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

If you can simplify the number, start by doing that. Then you must decide if the number can also be written as a fraction of two integers. If it can, then it is a rational number; if it cannot, then it is irrational.

Rational numbers can always be written as a fraction with two integers (although they may not always look like a fraction!). For example, 5 is a rational number because you can write it as a fraction like this: 5151. 101101 is equal to 1010, and so it can be written as a fraction with two integers.

The correct answer is rational.

    ==−(3)−32(3)13(3)−56−(3)−32(3)(13)+(−56)−(3)−32(3)−12−(3)−32(3)13(3)−56=−(3)−32(3)(13)+(−56)=−(3)−32(3)−12

    Now use the rule for exponents in fractions: subtract the lower exponent from the upper one:

    ==−(3)−32(3)−12−(3)(−32)−(−12)−(3)−1−(3)−32(3)−12=−(3)(−32)−(−12)=−(3)−1

    After all of that, all of those roots simplify to −1−1, and the answer is −13−13.

  2. What type of number is the answer?

    Answer:
    HINT: <no title>
    [−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

    Rational numbers have a tight connection to fractions. Integers are very nice and tidy numbers. Irrational numbers are never-ending, non-repeating decimal numbers like surds.

    STEP: <no title>
    [−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]
    A rational number is any number which can be written as a fraction with an integer in the numerator and another integer in the denominator (as long as the denominator is not zero). Therefore, −13−13 is a rational number.

Evaluating trigonometric expressions

Evaluate the following trigonometric expression without using a calculator:

tan30°+tan30°tan⁡30°+tan⁡30°
Answer:
HINT: <no title>
[−0 points ⇒ 2 / 2 points left]

Both of the angles given in the expression are special angles. Start by evaluating each of the trigonometric ratios of these special angles. Then reduce the resulting expression.

STEP: Evaluate each of the trigonometric ratios
[−1 point ⇒ 1 / 2 points left]

The question asks us to evaluate this expression:

tan30°+tan30°tan⁡30°+tan⁡30°

One way to find the answer would be to type this into a calculator. But we have been told not to use one!

We need to realise here that the angles in the expresseion are both special angles. This means that we can determine the values of the trigonometric ratios exactly.

Evaluating each of the terms, we know that

tan30°tan30°=13‾√=13‾√tan⁡30°=13tan⁡30°=13

Substituting these values into the original expression, we get

tan30°+tan30°=13‾√+13‾√tan⁡30°+tan⁡30°=13+13
NOTE: You need to know the trigonometric ratios of the special angles for tests and exams. If you can't remember all of the ratios, start by drawing the special triangles. Then evaluate the ratio using the pictures.
STEP: Simplify the substituted expression
[−1 point ⇒ 0 / 2 points left]

Now that we have the values of each of the terms in the expression, we can simplify to get the final answer:

tan30°+tan30°=13‾√+13‾√=23‾√tan⁡30°+tan⁡30°=13+13=23

So the correct answer is:

tan30°+tan30°=23‾√tan⁡30°+tan⁡30°=23
